{
  "act_id": "act_range_calc",
  "title": "Computing the Range — Time Meets Distance",
  "viz_panel": "svg",
  "beats": [
    {
      "say": "We have the clock — $t = \\frac{10\\sqrt{2}}{4.9} \\approx 2.89$ seconds, glowing gold. Now the horizontal equation. No acceleration, no drag — just constant speed times time.",
      "card": null,
      "viz_actions": [
        {
          "method": "resetSegment",
          "params": {
            "keepIds": [
              "trajectoryArc",
              "apexDot",
              "axes"
            ]
          },
          "offset": "0"
        },
        {
          "method": "showEquation",
          "params": {
            "step": "horizontal",
            "position": "center"
          },
          "offset": "+0.8"
        }
      ],
      "inline_viz": null,
      "duration": null
    },
    {
      "say": "The horizontal component of our launch speed is $v_0 \\cos 45° = 10\\sqrt{2}$ m/s. So $x(t) = 10\\sqrt{2} \\cdot t$ — clean and linear all the way to landing.",
      "card": {
        "type": "latex",
        "content": "x(t) = v_0 \\cos\\theta \\cdot t = 10\\sqrt{2}\\cdot t",
        "highlight": false
      },
      "viz_actions": [
        {
          "method": "dimAllExcept",
          "params": {
            "exceptIds": [
              "trajectoryArc",
              "axes",
              "equationBlock"
            ],
            "opacity": 0.2
          },
          "offset": "+0.5"
        }
      ],
      "inline_viz": null,
      "duration": null
    },
    {
      "say": "Now substitute. The flight time $t = \\frac{10\\sqrt{2}}{4.9}$ slides straight in — and watch what happens to those square roots.",
      "card": null,
      "viz_actions": [
        {
          "method": "substituteTime",
          "params": {
            "t": 2.887
          },
          "offset": "+0.6"
        }
      ],
      "inline_viz": null,
      "duration": null
    },
    {
      "say": "The two $\\sqrt{2}$ factors multiply: $10\\sqrt{2} \\times 10\\sqrt{2} = 100 \\times 2 = 200$. The roots vanish completely, leaving just $\\frac{200}{4.9}$.",
      "card": {
        "type": "derivation",
        "title": "Range Calculation",
        "steps": [
          {
            "latex": "R = 10\\sqrt{2} \\cdot \\dfrac{10\\sqrt{2}}{4.9}"
          },
          {
            "latex": "= \\dfrac{10\\sqrt{2} \\times 10\\sqrt{2}}{4.9} = \\dfrac{200}{4.9}",
            "highlight": false
          },
          {
            "latex": "\\approx 40.8 \\text{ m}",
            "highlight": true
          }
        ]
      },
      "viz_actions": [],
      "inline_viz": null,
      "duration": null
    },
    {
      "say": "Forty-point-eight meters. Watch it land — the bracket stretches from launch to exactly where the arc touches down. That gold label is your answer.",
      "card": null,
      "viz_actions": [
        {
          "method": "drawRangeBracket",
          "params": {
            "range": 40.8
          },
          "offset": "0"
        }
      ],
      "inline_viz": "svg",
      "duration": null
    }
  ]
